The paper deals with sentiment classification, which is a subfield of natural language processing (NLP) and falls under the category of computer science (cs). The use of logic rules in sentiment classification is a common approach, which suggests that the paper could belong to the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning). Additionally, the paper also discusses the use of contextualized embeddings, which is a popular technique in NLP and could place the paper under the sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language). The paper also mentions the use of crowdsourcing, which is a common approach in artificial intelligence (AI) research, suggesting that it could belong to the sub-category of cs.AI. The paper's focus on performance analysis and visualizations could also place it under the sub-categories of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) and cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition).
